    <section class="main-section" id="Introduction">
      <header>Introduction</header>
      <p>Python is a high-level, general-purpose programming language. Its design philosophy emphasizes code readability with the use of significant indentation. Python is dynamically typed and garbage-collected. It supports multiple programming paradigms, including structured, object-oriented and functional programming.</p>
      <p>Steps on getting started with Python:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Open Python.org</li>
        <li>Select the right Python verison</li>
        <li>Download Python IDLE onto your computer</li>
        <li>Open Python</li>
        <li>Done!</li>   
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="main-section" id="Data_Types">
      <header>Data Types</header>
      <p>Python currently supports a variety of different data types, which are essential for storing and manipulating different kinds of information. Here are some fundamental Python data types:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Integers (int)
        </li>
        <p>Used for whole numbers without any decimal points.
          <p class="example">Example: x = 5</p>
        </p>
        <li>
          Floats (float)
        </li>
        <p>Used for numbers with decimal points.
          <p class="example">Example: x = 3.14</p>
        </p>
        <li>
          Strings (str)
        </li>
        <p>Used for sequences of characters, enclosed in single (' '), double (" "), or triple (''' ' ''') quotes
          <p class="example">Example = "Hello World!"</p>
        </p>
        <li>
          Booleans (bool) 
        </li>
        <p>Used for representing truth values, either True or False.
          <p class="example">Example = 'is_python_fun = True'</p>
        </p>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="main-section" id="Hello_World!">
      <header>Hello World!</header>
      <p>Let's print your first ever line of code! The most iconic phrase first time coders use is "Hello World!"</p>
      <p>Try it out on Python:</p>
      <code>print("Hello World!")</code>
      <p>Go ahead and try out other sentences with the <code>print()</code> function, such as:</p>
      <p><code>print("My name is John!")</code></p>
      <p><code>print("Hi Mom!")</code></p>
      <p><code>print("I love Python")</code></p>
    </section>

    <section class="main-section" id="Numbers">
      <header>Numbers</header>
      <p> Python interpreter functions like a basic calculator, allowing you to input expressions, and it will output the computed values. The syntax for expressions is simple: you can use the standard arithmetic operators (+, -, *, /) for mathematical operations, and parentheses (()) for grouping.
      </p>
      <p>For example:</p>
      <p><code>print(2 + 2)</code></p>
      <p><code>print(10 / 2)</code></p>
      <p><code>print(5 * 10 + 2)</code></p>
    </section>

    <section class="main-section" id="If_Statements">
      <header>If Statements</header>
      <p>the if statement is a fundamental control structure that allows you to conditionally execute a block of code based on a specified condition. Here's a brief explanation:</p>
      <pre>
        <code>
        x = 10
        if x > 5:
            print("x is greater than 5")
        </code>
      </pre>
      <pre>
        <code>
        y = 3
        if y % 2 == 0:
            print("y is even")
        else:
            print("y is odd")
        </code>
      </pre>
      <pre>
        <code>
        z = 0
        if z > 0:
            print("z is positive")
        elif z < 0:
            print("z is negative")
        else:
            print("z is zero")
        </code>
      </pre>
    </section>

    <section class="main-section" id="While_Statements">
      <header>While Statements</header>
      <p>A while statement is used to create a loop that continues executing as long as a specified condition is true. The general syntax of a while loop in Python is as follows:</p>
      <pre>
        <code>
          # Example: Counting down from 5 to 1
          count = 5

          while count > 0:
              print(count)
              count -= 1

          print("Blast off!")
        </code>
      </pre>
    </section>

    <footer>
      <header>Reference</header>
